{"parse":{"title":"Monty Cantsin","pageid":338206,"revid":769824423,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Monty Cantsin</b> is a <a href=\"/wiki/Multiple-use_name\" title=\"Multiple-use name\">multiple-use name</a> that anyone can adopt, but has close ties to <a href=\"/wiki/Neoism\" title=\"Neoism\">Neoism</a>. Monty Cantsin was originally conceived as an \"open pop star.\" In a philosophy anticipating that of <a href=\"/wiki/Free_software\" title=\"Free software\">free software</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Open_source\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Open source\">open source</a>, anyone could perform in his name and thus contribute to and participate in his fame and achievements. \n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Influences\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Influences</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Publications\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Publications</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Monty_Cantsin&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The name was coined in 1978 by the critic, prankster and <a href=\"/wiki/Mail_Art\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Mail Art\">Mail Artist</a> <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=David_Zack&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"David Zack (page does not exist)\">David Zack</a> as a <a href=\"/wiki/Nom_de_plume\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Nom de plume\">nom de plume</a> for the <a href=\"/wiki/Latvia\" title=\"Latvia\">Latvian</a>-born poet and singer <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Maris_Kundzins&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Maris Kundzins (page does not exist)\">Maris Kundzins</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Carr2012_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Carr2012-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  It further alludes to: \n</p>\n<ul><li>Martial Canterel, the wizard-hero of <a href=\"/wiki/Raymond_Roussel\" title=\"Raymond Roussel\">Raymond Roussel</a>'s novel <i><a href=\"/wiki/Locus_Solus\" title=\"Locus Solus\">Locus Solus</a></i>;</li>\n<li>Monte Capanno, a Northern <a href=\"/wiki/Italy\" title=\"Italy\">Italian</a> villa near Perugia where Zack had taught a San Jose State College study and living community in 1970;</li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Monte_Cazazza\" title=\"Monte Cazazza\">Monte Cazazza</a>, a Californian <a href=\"/wiki/Performance_art\" title=\"Performance art\">performance</a> artist and <a href=\"/wiki/Industrial_music\" title=\"Industrial music\">industrial music</a> performer;</li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Istvan_Kantor\" title=\"Istvan Kantor\">Istvan Kantor</a>, the second bearer of the name;</li>\n<li>\"Monty can't sing\";</li>\n<li>\"Monty can't sin\", a reference to religious free spirit movements which collectively adopted the names of <a href=\"/wiki/Jesus\" title=\"Jesus\">Jesus</a> or <a href=\"/wiki/Saint\" title=\"Saint\">saints</a>.</li></ul>\n<p>Zack called upon his correspondents to adopt the name Monty Cantsin. His suggestion was taken up in 1979 by the <a href=\"/wiki/Hungarian-Canadian\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Hungarian-Canadian\">Hungarian-Canadian</a> performance artist <a href=\"/wiki/Istvan_Kantor\" title=\"Istvan Kantor\">Istvan Kantor</a>, who amalgamated the name into <a href=\"/wiki/Neoism\" title=\"Neoism\">Neoism</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Carr2012_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Carr2012-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> As the shared identity of all <a href=\"/wiki/Neoists\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Neoists\">Neoists</a>, Monty Cantsin was transformed from a \"pop star\" to a radical identity experiment occupying the everyday life of <a href=\"/wiki/Neoists\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Neoists\">Neoists</a> and culminating in frequently extremist ways at Neoist Apartment Festivals (\"APTs\"). The \"open pop star\" concept lived on in a series of <a href=\"/wiki/Electropop\" title=\"Electropop\">electropop</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Industrial_music\" title=\"Industrial music\">industrial music</a> albums and performances of, mainly, <a href=\"/wiki/Istvan_Kantor\" title=\"Istvan Kantor\">Istvan Kantor</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Influences\">Influences</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Monty_Cantsin&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Influences\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Later multiple names like <a href=\"/wiki/Karen_Eliot\" title=\"Karen Eliot\">Karen Eliot</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Luther_Blissett_(nom_de_plume)\" title=\"Luther Blissett (nom de plume)\">Luther Blissett</a> drew inspiration from Monty Cantsin and <a href=\"/wiki/Neoism\" title=\"Neoism\">Neoism</a>, but intentionally avoided association with physical persons, being conceived either as mere signatures (Eliot), collective media phantoms (Blissett) or multiple single collective experiments.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Publications\">Publications</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Monty_Cantsin&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Publications\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>(as editor): <i>Neoist Book</i>, Canada, 1984. <sup id=\"cite_ref-cas84_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-cas84-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Monty_Cantsin&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Carr2012-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Carr2012_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Carr2012_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">C. Carr (9 April 2012). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=QX9ZSOWJO-gC&amp;pg=PA105\"><i>On Edge: Performance at the End of the Twentieth Century</i></a>. Wesleyan University Press. pp.&#160;105\u2013. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-8195-7242-4\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0-8195-7242-4\">978-0-8195-7242-4</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=On+Edge%3A+Performance+at+the+End+of+the+Twentieth+Century&amp;rft.pages=105-&amp;rft.pub=Wesleyan+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2012-04-09&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-8195-7242-4&amp;rft.au=C.+Carr&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DQX9ZSOWJO-gC%26pg%3DPA105&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMonty+Cantsin\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-cas84-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-cas84_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"> <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://www.neoism.info/neoist_book.pdf\">http://www.neoism.info/neoist_book.pdf</a>. URL last accessed 2014-04-07.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1326\nCached time: 20180908093938\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.084 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.102 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 154/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 1931/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 77/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 1858/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.031/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 1.33 MB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   77.543      1 Template:Reflist\n100.00%   77.543      1 -total\n 80.04%   62.064      1 Template:Cite_book\n  3.20%    2.479      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:338206-0!canonical and timestamp 20180908093938 and revision id 769824423\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[{"lang":"de","url":"https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monty_Cantsin","langname":"German","autonym":"Deutsch","*":"Monty Cantsin"}],"categories":[{"sortkey":"Cantsin, Monty","*":"Anonymity_pseudonyms"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Neoism"}],"links":[{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Electropop"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Free software"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Hungarian-Canadian"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Industrial music"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"International Standard Book Number"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Istvan Kantor"},{"ns":0,"exists":"",